ğŸ“š Student Attendance Analysis & Prediction
ğŸ“Œ Project Overview
This project performs an in-depth Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) and statistical testing on a student dataset to identify the key drivers of class attendance.
The goal is to understand how factors like demographics, study habits, weather, and logistics influence whether a student attends class.
ğŸ“‚ Dataset Overview
The dataset consists of 20,000 student records with 15 features, including:
Demographics: age, gender, parent_education.
Academic: course, year, study_hours, attendance (Target: 0 or 1).
Logistics & Environment: travel_time_minutes, hostel_resident, internet_access, class_type (Online/Offline), weather.
Health: sleep_hours.
Data Quality:The dataset is clean with no missing values and no duplicate rows.
ğŸ” Key Insights & Conclusions1. ğŸ“– Study Habits & Attendance
Strong Correlation: There is a highly significant relationship between the number of hours a student studies and their attendance.
Statistical Proof: An Independent T-Test yielded a P-value of ~1.03e-182, overwhelmingly rejecting the null hypothesis.
This confirms that students who attend class tend to have significantly different (likely higher) study hours than those who do not.
2. â›ˆï¸ The Impact of Weather & Class TypeWeather Matters: Weather conditions significantly impact attendance rates.
Interaction Effect: The analysis highlights a critical interaction between weather and class_type.
Adverse weather (e.g., rain, storms) disproportionately affects Offline class attendance, while Online class attendance remains relatively stable.
Statistical Proof: A Chi-Square test between weather and attendance resulted in a P-value of ~6.60e-43, confirming that the dependency is statistically significant.
3. ğŸšŒ Logistics: Travel & ResidenceTravel Time: Students with longer travel times generally show lower attendance or more variance in attendance, as visualized in the violin plots.
Hostel Residents: Analysis suggests that students living in hostels (closer to campus) likely have different attendance patterns compared to day scholars, often showing higher stability.
4. ğŸ’» InfrastructureInternet Access: Students with internet access tend to have slightly better attendance rates, likely facilitating participation in online classes.
